heir lives go beyond the call of duty to ensure the safety of the public. A first responder serves their community by performing their high-risk occupation. In the line of duty, first responders can face injury and need medication to treat their wounds and physical ailments. When being injured on the job, first responders may not receive full treatment or pharmaceuticals through medical insurance or workers compensation. Not receiving the medication needed puts a physical strain on first responders, especially during the long hours they work. </span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">First Responders Network understands the dedication and commitment of those individuals who answer the call. Our goal is to assist first responders by educating them on the facets of their workers compensation claims and health insurance, so they may receive the proper medical treatment. Insurance companies may only offer first responders partial or no medication. In some instances, the cost of medication at the pharmacy may be an exorbitant amount for first responders. </span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>Pharmaceutical Treatment:</b>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Working a strenuous and physically demanding job asserts a tremendous amount of strain on the body. It can not only affect various muscle groups, but it can also be mentally stressful. The body becomes sore which causes aches and pains to develop. This makes it difficult for first responders to perform their duties, especially for those working in difficult conditions in Florida. Medicine is expensive especially for first responders whose insurance doesnt fully cover the cost. This is also true for first responders who file workers compensation claims after receiving an injury during work. </span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Thankfully, legislation in Florida has been passed to assist first responders with medical conditions such as hypertension, heart disease, or tuberculosis. Prescription medication for the treatment of these medical conditions can be a costly trip to the drugstore for first responders. Here are some of the benefits that first responders can qualify for from the Heart and Lung Bill.</span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><b>Prescribed course of treatment</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> - means prescribed medicines for the specific disease or diseases claimed are compensated through the Heart and Lung Bill. </span></li>\r\n 	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><b>Independent medical examination</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> - In the event of a dispute in the appropriateness of prescribed medical treatment by the physician, an independent medical evaluation can be requested. </span></li>\r\n 	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><b>Qualification for prescribed course of treatment</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> - Your personal physician determines employment departure is caused by significant arrigrivation of hypertension, tuberculosis, and heart disease, then they will prescribe your treatment plan.</span></li>\r\n 	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><b>Workers Compensation</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> - Medical treatment through a workers compensation claim is determined if the employees departure was due to aggravated symptoms of heart disease, high blood pressure, and tuberculosis. Medications for these conditions are granted under the Heart and Lung Bill.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Researching your insurance policy or workers comp claim to see if you qualify for health benefits can be difficult. Having guidance sifting through the legalities of policies can leave you without receiving your full benefits. If you believe your health has been affected by work, but are unsure if you qualify for health-related benefits from the Heart and Lung Bill, let First Responders Network assist you. Our team of experts can walk you through 